25: // Main message for a rate limit request. The rate limit service is designed to be fully generic
26: // in the sense that it can operate on arbitrary hierarchical key/value pairs. The loaded
27: // configuration will parse the request and find the most specific limit to apply. In addition,
28: // a RateLimitRequest can contain multiple "descriptors" to limit on. When multiple descriptors
29: // are provided, the server will limit on *ALL* of them and return an OVER_LIMIT response if any
30: // of them are over limit. This enables more complex application level rate limiting scenarios
31: // if desired.
32: message RateLimitRequest {
33:   // All rate limit requests must specify a domain. This enables the configuration to be per
34:   // application without fear of overlap. E.g., "envoy".
35:   string domain = 1;
36: 
37:   // All rate limit requests must specify at least one RateLimitDescriptor. Each descriptor is
38:   // processed by the service (see below). If any of the descriptors are over limit, the entire
39:   // request is considered to be over limit.
